 Landing a job

Hiring Challenges

Working in a SOC is an exciting adventure that offers well-paid salaries but comes with a price. During their daily battles, security analysts and SOC management face many challenges.
 

A survey, "A SANS 2021 Survey: Security Operations Center (SOC)," conducted by Chris Crowley and John Pescatore in October 2021, stated the top challenges faced by SOCs. One of the survey questions was, "What is the greatest challenge (barrier) concerning the full utilization of your SOC capabilities by the entire organization?" Here is the answers summary:

 
The two most significant challenges were "Lack of skilled staff" and "Lack of automation and orchestration." Based on many insights from recruiters and HR managers, finding suitable candidates for cybersecurity positions is tough, and there is an evident shortage of cybersecurity skills, especially in the case of SOC analyst positions. On the other hand, juniors complain that it's hard to find a security job, although they have the required skills. Let's look at this from the perspectives of the hiring manager and job seeker.

It takes a lot of work for hiring managers to find skilled candidates for many reasons. Thousands of security job seekers are applying for any opening, claiming they have the necessary skills. It's a complex and time-consuming process to filter these applications and validate each candidate's technical expertise. The security market is over-saturated with certifications, and almost all candidates will hold a cert or two. Certificates are not and will never guarantee a candidate's expertise. They are only indicators that the candidate has spent considerable time, money, and effort to educate himself about a set of technical domains.


The SOC analyst position requires a good technical background, and acquiring all the necessary skills takes time and effort. In a famous book called "Ten Strategies of a World-Class SOC" by Carson Zimmerman, the author explains why a good analyst is better than many mediocre ones. And I quote from the 5th strategy chapter: "Analyst quality is vastly more important than analyst quantity." 

Looking at the other side, job seekers suffer from the same problem. It takes work for competent candidates to stand out from the crowd and land a decent job. Now, you may be thinking, what is the solution to this problem? In particular, as a job seeker since this is the relevant part for you.

 

The solution

The answer is to make it easier for the hiring manager to spot your technical competency in a verifiable way. By verifiable, we mean things that others cannot replicate or reproduce, such as open-source projects. Let's break this down further.

Getting a security job is like selling a product. Guess what the product is? It's you. This exercise can be divided into the following stages:

  1. The product: you are the product you try to sell, and the best way to ensure you are a high-quality product is to continually assess your skills measurably. Ensure that your skills are improving over time.
    • Bad example: depending on certifications alone to improve your skills.
    • Good example: utilizing practical and hands-on ways to evaluate your skills over time, such as Github side projects, Bug bounty programs, and practical labs.
       
  2. Sales Channel: the place where you can sell the product. Selling the product in the right place increases the odds of successful deals. Imagine a guy selling snorkeling masks in a non-coastal city! The product may be good, but it's not the right place to sell it. A good place is where your customers exist, customers with the expertise to judge the quality of your technical skills.
    • Bad example: recruitment sites, even with a security opening. Your application will be with thousands of other irrelevant applications. Even if it could make it, it will be reviewed by an HR personnel who cannot evaluate your skills.
    • Good examples: Github and Linkedin. Contributing to open-source security projects or writing security tools is an authentic experience that validates your skills. Sharing your Github stuff on Linkedin will catch security professionals' attention and probably can get you a decent job.
       
  3. Marketing: The way you market the product has a significant impact on the selling process. For example, selling snorkeling masks in a coastal city but in a closed box does not show the product inside or list product features and advantages.
    • Bad example: an incomplete Linkedin profile that needs a proper title, job duties, skills, certifications, etc.
    • Good example: an authentic Linkedin profile with proper location and keywords relevant to your skills, featuring your work, experience, and contributions.
       
  4. Customers: regardless of how good your selling strategies are, you need customers to buy your product. For example, selling high-quality snorkeling masks with proper marketing in a coastal but unpopulated city. The more customers who will see your product, the more the number of successful sales. Think of places where there will be many individuals interested in your profile!
    • Bad example: A fully-blown Linkedin profile with few connections.
    • Good example: a LinkedIn account with more than 1000 connections relevant to your industry and area of expertise. If you are a SOC analyst, connect with SOC analysts, leads, and managers in your location.

Do you know that salespeople get paid more than engineers? That's why you should pay great attention to your non-technical skills, not only if you are looking for a job but also if you want to achieve good results.
